# Data Layer Conventions

## Repository — parse responses, return Either

```dart
// ✅ Correct
Future<Either<Failure, UserModel>> getUser(String id) async {
  final result = await _dataSource.getUser(id);
  return result.fold(
    left,
    (response) => right(UserModel.fromJson(response.data['data'])),
  );
}
```

- Use lowercase `left` / `right()` from dartz — never `Left.new` / `Right(...)`.
- Never throw from a repository — always catch and return `left(failure)`.
- Repository only calls its own DataSource; it does not access `Dio` directly.

**Failure types** (`core/error/failure.dart`):

| Class | When to use |
|---|---|
| `ServerFailure` | 4xx / 5xx API responses |
| `NetworkFailure` | Timeout or no connectivity |
| `SystemFailure` | Unexpected Dart exceptions (e.g. JSON parse error) |

## DataSource — thin HTTP wrapper only

```dart
class UserDataSource extends ApiClient {
  const UserDataSource({required super.dio});

  Future<Either<Failure, Response>> getUser(String id) =>
      requestAPI(() => dio.get('/users/$id'));
}
```

- Extends `ApiClient`, calls `requestAPI()`.
- Returns raw `Either<Failure, Response>` — no JSON parsing here.
- One `DataSource` per feature; no god-object shared sources.

## Models — Freezed + json_serializable

```dart
@freezed
abstract class UserModel with _$UserModel {
  const factory UserModel({
    required String id,
    required String name,
    String? email,
    @JsonKey(defaultValue: false) required bool isActive,
  }) = _UserModel;

  factory UserModel.fromJson(Map<String, dynamic> json) =>
      _$UserModelFromJson(json);
}
```

- Always declare both part directives at the top of the file:
  ```dart
  part 'my_model.g.dart';
  part 'my_model.freezed.dart';
  ```
- Use `@JsonKey(defaultValue: ...)` for nullable or defaultable fields.
- After any model edit: `dart run build_runner build --delete-conflicting-outputs`
